Quoted By: >>58071171 >>58071540 >>58081321
>>58047065
I know I'm a bit late, but
>How's the next chapter coming?
It's done, I just have to edit. Like, a lot. But I think I've got it now.
>Planning a new story?
Always. The problem is my backlog of 'cool story' ideas gets added to far quicker than I can get through the current stuff I'm writing.
>Why did you choose this character?
I love her.
>What's something you want to improve?
My ability to distance myself when I edit. I'm confident in the small-scale stuff, but I struggle distancing myself from it to look at larger-scale issues. I can sometimes recognize them, but usually not in the same depth as I do when I look over others' work.
>What's something you want to see others improve?
Unironically reading others' work and talking about it. There's so many writers here with varying talents, interests, and abilities, same with readers; it's a shame that there's rarely any interplay going on.
I'm trying to improve on it myself, too.

Anonymous Mon 17 Jul 2023 03:51:20 No.58077725 Report
Quoted By:
>>58077100
You probably do have something to add and don't realize it. A fair few authors will make major edits to their draft depending on audience reaction, and many more will at least make minor tweaks. This can be good or bad, but if a change results in a story that the readers enjoy more, I consider it a plus.
"I'm really interested in this character and want to see more development" tells the author that people resonate with that character, or that other characters should get more focus so readers get invested in them too. Even if you go with something more simple like "I don't like where the plot's going" or "I feel like I've read this before" might encourage a writer to alter his plot beats to make his narrative a bit more unique or palatable.
You can make an argument that it might not be the platonic ideal of artistic expression, but if your goal is to write things people will read, pandering to your audience a smidge isn't going to kill your story.
>>58077208
You're contributing to the thread so I don't see an issue with it. Just recognize that people will get upset if you're too hard on their favorites, but also don't mask your true feelings about a piece. Kissing ass helps nobody.
